But there probably couldn't be a more damning indictment of the ISI than this.What such a highpowered commission seemed to be saying was that there is no way for anyone to tell if the ISI is guilty or innocent, because it functions beyond the pale of law and its work culture makes its accountability impossible. And we should change this state of affairs because people of this country believe that their intelligence agencies are mixed up in "heinous crime." Likewise, the Osama bin Laden incident was an intelligence failure, but there has been no accountability as there is no way to tell who within the ISI screwed up.The twin ideas that creating laws is pointless when there always remains a gap between a law and its implementation, and that the luxury of upholding fundamental rights can't be afforded in a country that is at war with itself are not new.
